Queue — first in, first out.

A queue allows insertions at one end — the rear — and removals from the other end — the front. The rule is the opposite of a stack: the first element inserted is the first one removed. This is called first in, first out, or F-I-F-O.

Think of a checkout line at a shop. New customers join the back of the queue. The cashier serves the person at the front. The person who has been waiting longest is served next. Nobody cuts in.

All four core operations are constant time: enqueue adds an element at the rear, dequeue removes and returns the element at the front, peek returns the front element without removing it, and is-empty checks whether the queue has any elements.
